import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="My Story | Hearts 2025/26">
  <section class="hero">
    <img class="hero-badge" src="/favicon.png" alt="" />

    <div class="hero-inner">
      <div class="hero-topline">
        <a href="/" class="hero-nav-link">← Home</a>
        <div>Heart of Midlothian • 2025/26</div>
      </div>

      <h1>My Story</h1>
      <h2>The self indulgent ramblings of an armchair fan in Dunblane.</h2>
      <h2>From the pain of '86 to the pride of '26.</h2>
      <h2>This is my story...</h2>

      <div class="stats">
        <a class="stat position-stat" href="#early-years">
          The<strong>Early Years</strong>
        </a>
        <a class="stat position-stat" href="#the-season">
          The<strong>Season</strong>
        </a>
        <a class="stat position-stat" href="#the-future">
          The<strong>Future</strong>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <main class="shell">
    <section id="early-years" class="match-section">
      <article class="panel" style="line-height:1.7">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <span>The Early Years</span>
        </div>
        <p>
          Skip this bit if you're only interested in the fitba. This is my own
          story about the 2025/26 season, so I'm gonna be indulgent and start
          from the beginning. One of my first memories was when a boy called Gav
          joined my class in Primary Two and asked me what football team I
          supported. My dad was (and still is) a rugby man, so I don't think I'd
          ever really thought about it. I said I was a Hibs fan, and he said
          Hibs were crap and I should be a Hearts fan. It was Corstorphine —
          well, Carrick Knowe actually, I'm just trying to posh myself up here —
          so it made sense. It was closer to Tynecastle. From then on, I was a
          Jambo. Having an egg-chaser as a dad, I didn't get to many games.
          Anyway, my family seemed to do something scouting- or guiding-related
          every day of the week, and given it was Thatcher's Scotland and my
          folks didn't have two pennies to rub together, the chances of me
          visiting Tynecastle were fairly limited. A man called Derek, who later
          became my scout leader, took me to a few games. I remember a Dumbarton
          game, a Motherwell game, and I was even there when PSG came to Tynie
          and we came away with a 2–2 draw. Then came '86. Those who remember it
          will sympathise with a ten-year-old boy sitting watching Ceefax and
          listening to Radio Scotland, seeing the images on the news of grown
          men greetin' their eyes out and throwing things at that moustachioed,
          curly-haired twat Albert Kidd. (Sorry for even mentioning his name.)
          Primary school — and Gav — came and went. High school beckoned. A new
          best pal, Derek (not my scout leader), and some more Jambos at
          Forrester High School. Still no money, and it was the 80s, so live
          football was limited. For years, everything was Hearts — Hearts
          bedsheets, Hearts wallpaper, Hearts annuals. I was Hearts daft. I
          lived round the corner from Neil Berry and saw him regularly. Posters
          of Robbo and Gary Mackay on every wall. We've all been there, and I
          wouldn't change it for anything. After high school, I went to Aberdeen
          for uni. I left Derek in Edinburgh working in the bank with his season
          ticket at Tynecastle. I got right into booze, drugs, and the ladies,
          and fitba took a back seat. Living with Rangers fans meant we still
          consumed football on the radio and the telly, but let's be honest — my
          mind was on other things. Missed the Bayern game, but don't regret it
          because I'd probably have been stoned or drunk somewhere. I left
          Aberdeen seven years later with my girlfriend and ended up back in
          Edinburgh. When Derek couldn't go to the fitba, I'd get his ticket, so
          I saw a good few games. He sat with his pal Rab where the "ultras"
          bang their drums now. Saw Barcelona beat us. We all remember those
          times. It was a rollercoaster, but thank Christ it's over. Move
          forward ten years. We can ignore a lot of the dark times for the
          Jambos. Ann Budge came into my kilt shop and I ended up getting
          involved in the new Hearts tartan. Did a photoshoot with John Souttar
          and Don Cowie and met loads of Jambo legends, including Craig Levein
          and Gary Locke. It was a great time. A few years later, Derek retired,
          moved away up north, and gave up his season ticket. By then, I was too
          embroiled in young family life to worry too much about visiting Tynie.
        </p>
      </article>

      <section id="the-season" class="match-section">
        <article class="panel" style="line-height:1.7">
          <div class="section-heading">
            <span>The Season</span>
          </div>
          <p>
            This is where the actual 2025/26 story starts — the matches, the
            madness, the hope, the panic, and the creeping realisation that
            something special might actually be happening.
          </p>
        </article>
      </section>

      <section id="the-future" class="match-section">
        <article class="panel" style="line-height:1.7">
          <div class="section-heading">
            <span>The Future</span>
          </div>
          <p>
            And then comes the dangerous bit: hope. Because supporting Hearts
            teaches you never to get carried away, right up until the exact
            moment you get completely carried away.
          </p>
        </article>
      </section>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
